---
<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/finviz-stocks" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Finviz Stocks: How to Use the Screener Like a Pro</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Stop guessing and start screening. Learn the exact filters and formulas used to spot breakout setups before the crowd.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Understanding Finviz and Its Power</h2>
    <p>When you hear traders talk about "Finviz stocks," they aren't referring to a specific asset class. For instance, you might use it to identify <a href="/high-flying-ai-stocks-to-sell">high flying AI stocks to sell</a> before a broader market correction. Instead, they are talking about equities discovered using one of the most powerful, free financial visualization tools available on the web today: Finviz (Financial Visualizations). For beginners and seasoned professionals alike, navigating the stock market without a reliable screener is akin to sailing across the ocean without a compass. You might eventually reach a destination, but the journey will be perilous and entirely dependent on luck rather than strategy.</p>

    <p>Finviz simplifies the incredibly complex world of market data by turning millions of data points into digestible, visual formats. Its homepage alone provides a heat map of the S&P 500, showing exactly which sectors are driving the market on any given day. But the true power of Finviz lies in its screener. By applying specific filters based on fundamental, technical, or descriptive criteria, you can instantly narrow down a universe of over 8,000 stocks to a handful of high-probability candidates.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>The Golden Screener Formula:</strong> For a balanced growth setup, set your filters to:
      <em>Market Cap: > Small ($300M+)</em> |
      <em>EPS Growth Next Year: > 10%</em> |
      <em>Relative Volume: > 1.5</em> |
      <em>Price: > SMA50</em>.
      This isolates companies growing earnings that are also experiencing unusually high buying interest and upward momentum.
    </div>

    <h2>Real-World Examples and Analogies</h2>
    <p>Imagine walking into a massive library with millions of books, but no indexing system. If you wanted a book about 19th-century European history written in French, you'd have to check every single book on every shelf. That is what trading feels like without a screener. Finviz acts as the ultimate digital librarian. You simply tell it exactly what you want—for instance, a profitable technology company trading below its intrinsic value with a recent surge in trading volume—and it hands you the exact list in seconds.</p>

    <p>Consider a real-world scenario from late last year. A mid-cap software company released a stellar earnings report, but it wasn't immediately picked up by mainstream financial news. However, its trading volume spiked to three times its normal daily average, and its price crossed above a critical moving average. A trader utilizing a simple relative volume and moving average crossover screen on Finviz would have spotted this anomaly instantly, entering the trade days before the broader market realized the stock's new valuation baseline.</p>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Fundamental vs. Technical Screening</h3>
      <p>Finviz allows you to blend two entirely different philosophies of investing seamlessly:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fundamental Filters:</strong> Focus on the underlying business health (e.g., P/E ratio, Debt-to-Equity, Return on Investment).</li>
        <li><strong>Technical Filters:</strong> Focus on price action and market psychology (e.g., RSI, Moving Averages, Chart Patterns like Head and Shoulders).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The most successful strategies often combine both—finding fundamentally sound companies that are currently exhibiting strong technical setups.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Why It Matters: Practical Implications</h2>
    <p>Understanding how to leverage Finviz is not just about saving time; it's about shifting your mindset from reactive to proactive. Most retail investors are reactive. They buy a stock because a friend recommended it, or because they saw a headline on a financial news network. By the time the news hits the mainstream, the "smart money" has already taken its position, and the retail investor is left buying at the top.</p>

    <p>Being proactive means defining your criteria for a good investment before you ever look at a stock ticker. It means relying on data rather than emotion. If the market is experiencing a severe downturn, you don't panic. Instead, you adjust your Finviz filters to look for companies with zero debt, high cash reserves, and a history of paying dividends during recessions. You let the tool cut through the noise and present you with actionable intelligence.</p>

    <p>Furthermore, the visual nature of Finviz helps in quickly assessing market breadth. This is crucial whether you're trading domestic equities or looking for uncorrelated returns in emerging or frontier markets, such as <a href="/nigeria-stocks">Nigeria stocks</a>. The heatmap allows you to see if a market rally is broad-based (many stocks across different sectors are green) or narrow (only a few mega-cap tech stocks are carrying the index). This macroeconomic perspective is vital for managing risk and adjusting your portfolio exposure accordingly.</p>

    <h2>Advanced Screening Techniques</h2>
    <p>Once you master the basics, you can begin to explore custom setups. For example, the "Short Squeeze" setup is incredibly popular among aggressive traders. By filtering for stocks with a high "Short Float" (e.g., over 20%) combined with strong recent performance (e.g., Price > SMA20), you can identify heavily shorted stocks that are starting to rise. When these stocks move higher, short sellers are forced to buy back shares to cover their losses, creating a rapid, explosive upward move.</p>

    <p>For long-term investors, the "Dividend Aristocrat" screen is invaluable. You can filter for companies in the S&P 500 that have a dividend yield over 2%, a payout ratio under 60% (ensuring the dividend is sustainable), and positive earnings growth. This yields a list of mature, stable companies that are likely to continue returning value to shareholders regardless of broader market volatility.</p>

    <p>By making Finviz a core part of your daily routine—running your screens after the market closes to prepare for the next day—you transform your investing approach from a series of random guesses into a disciplined, repeatable, and scalable business.</p>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Is Finviz free to use?</summary>
        <p>Yes, Finviz offers a robust free tier that includes delayed quotes, basic screening tools, and charting capabilities. However, real-time data and advanced features require a premium subscription.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I screen for breakout stocks on Finviz?</summary>
        <p>To screen for breakouts, look for stocks with high relative volume (over 1.5), price near a 52-week high, and a technical pattern like a wedge or channel breakout using the 'Pattern' filter.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What does 'Relative Volume' mean on Finviz?</summary>
        <p>Relative volume compares a stock's current trading volume to its average historical volume. A relative volume over 1 indicates the stock is trading more heavily than usual, often a sign of institutional interest or news.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I use Finviz for day trading?</summary>
        <p>While the free version of Finviz has delayed data (which is not suitable for day trading), the Elite subscription provides real-time data and intraday charts that day traders can utilize effectively.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the best Finviz screener setting for value investing?</summary>
        <p>Value investors often filter for a P/E ratio under 15, a Price-to-Book ratio under 2, positive EPS growth, and a dividend yield over 2%. These settings help identify potentially undervalued companies.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>
